[Event "Baker Bridge - Reverse Bids"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:KQJ64.AKJ76.K6.5 98.Q53.JT7.K7632 T75.82.AQ53.JT84 A32.T94.9842.AQ9"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
1S pass 2S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "20376091cbbbbb34fd6570a4fa0452817327d32f5d4a6ab0da6a6057b7d3ae17"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/reverse_bids"]
[Student "S"]
{It may be tempting to open 1\H, planning on Reversing in \S at your second turn to show your big hand.

Don't. A Reverse should always show an unbalanced hand with the first suit longer. So you open 1\S and partner replies 2\S.

If you had opened 1\H partner would have replied 1NT. Then when you Reversed with 2\S he would have assumed you had a 4-card \S suit and would probably have put you back in \Hs, your known 5-card suit.

Things would have gotten confusing, to say the least.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "E:AK.52.A642.AKT74 J9852.QT43.JT.63 T74.KJ98.K73.985 Q63.A76.Q985.QJ2"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3C"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1C pass 1H pass 2D pass 3C pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "ddeceb7f7f9d7cbd9745795acd2d96b11a25f33d2602a37fdb8c13d64a444eea"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/reverse_bids"]
[Student "S"]
{You would really love to pass. You have a terrible hand and you like the \Ds better than the \Cs.

But you are forced to bid. And since partner has 5 \Cs and only 4 \Ds, you should take him back to his first suit.

Mercifully he passes.}

